    <title>Combined summary - Service bits for pruned nodes</title>
    <updated>2023-06-06T15:53:23.524428+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2013-April/002461.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developers have been discussing various proposals related to improving the efficiency and flexibility of the peer-to-peer (P2P) network. One suggestion is to split nodes into "storage/bandwidth nodes" and "validating nodes," as these are independent functions, which could improve optimization.Peer discovery has been a significant topic of discussion, with IRC code deleted due to server issues, and DNS seeds no longer used as a mechanism for seeding but rather as a means of choosing all peers. Developers have proposed using DHT capable BitTorrent clients or libraries to ensure historic data storage and replication amongst nodes. Pieter Wuille has proposed pruning nodes that do not keep historic blocks around, and two extra service bits, NODE_VALIDATE and NODE_BLOCKS_2016, have been suggested to ensure new and old nodes can find peers to synchronize from.Furthermore, the Bitcoin network is considering ways to ensure that historic data is properly stored and replicated amongst its nodes, such as randomly storing chunks according to available space and giving priority to "N most recent" chunks for more replicas in the network. While BitTorrent is one implementation, it may not be suitable due to publicity concerns.In an email conversation, John Dillon suggested using BitTorrent to solve the problem of offering up storage capacity, but this idea was met with several objections. The writer suggests optimizing P2P peer discovery should be prioritized over optimizing centralized services, specifically DNS seeds. Although DNS seeds are necessary for obtaining the initial set of peers, the message includes alternative means of peer discovery such as search engines, IPv4 scanning, and anycast peers.The conversation focuses on improving the flexibility and efficiency of node pruning in Bitcoin by allowing nodes to choose their own ranges to keep rather than having fixed chosen intervals. In another email exchange, John Dillon encourages the development of better bootstrap mechanisms.Overall, the discussions focused on improving the flexibility and efficiency of storing and transmitting Bitcoin blocks while addressing concerns about reliability and security. The discussion revolves around finding new ways to store and transmit Bitcoin blocks that make it less likely for Bitcoin to be shut down worldwide.The discussion revolves around the issue of node pruning in Bitcoin, with multiple proposed solutions. In 2013, Ricardo Filipe suggested using a Distributed Hash Table (DHT) to organize blockchain data, but Jeff Garzik argued that this could make the chain vulnerable to DoS attacks. Pieter Wuille proposed pruning nodes that do not keep historic blocks around and adding two extra service bits to the P2P protocol. Mike Hearn and Pieter discussed giving nodes more flexibility in choosing which ranges to keep and how to advertise their pruned status. Gregory Maxwell dismissed the idea of using BitTorrent to distribute the blockchain due to concerns about reliability and potential attacks. In an email conversation, Mike Hearn suggests representing the policy as "I keep the last N blocks," and adding a field to the version announcement that announces the actual first block served. The idea of splitting nodes into "storage/bandwidth nodes" and "validating nodes" is discussed. The email conversation between Peter Todd and John Dillon discusses the possibility of using BitTorrent technology in the Bitcoin network. The main idea is to use analysis by clients of the part distribution, which allows a client to download and share the least-propagated parts first to maintain high availability of the whole file.Finally, in a discussion about DNS caching and seed values, there is concern that cacheable responses could lead to a sudden influx of traffic at one set of nodes if a large ISP caches a response. The author of the message apologizes for using the term "discovery" instead of "bootstrapping" and argues that centralized methods like DNS should only be used for initial bootstrapping and development efforts should focus on non-centralized peer discovery mechanisms.</summary>
